<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<pretext>
  <article xml:id="article">
    
    <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25in" xml:id="ws-ibp">
      <title>Worksheet for Section 6.1</title>

      <objectives>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use integration by parts to find the antiderivative of a product of functions.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Use integration by parts to evaluate definite integrals.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </objectives>


      <page>
        <exercisegroup>
        <title>The basics</title>

        <introduction>
          <p>
            Evaluate the integrals, integrating by parts.
            In the case of a definite integral, your answer should be a number.
            For indefinite integrals, your answer should be the most general antiderivative (this means donâ€™t forget <m>+C</m>).
          </p>

          <p>
            Think about your choices of <m>u</m> and <m>dv</m>.
            Why did you decide the way you did?
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int x\sin 2x \,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>

          </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int t^2 \cos t\,dt</m>
            </p>
          </statement>

          </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int_1^2 x \ln x\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>

          </exercise>
        </exercisegroup>
      </page>


      <page>
        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <title>Dirty Tricks, part I</title>

          <introduction>
            <p>
              We will use integration by parts twice to find <m>\int e^{-2x}\sin 3x\,dx</m>.
            </p>
          </introduction>


          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                First use <m>u = \sin 3x</m>, <m>dv = e^{-2x}\,dx</m>.
                The result should contain another integral suitable for integration by parts.
              </p>
            </statement>

            </task>


          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Find the remaining integral by parts using <m>dv = \cos 3x\,dx</m> (or some constant multiple of <m>\cos 3x</m>).
                What happens?
              </p>
            </statement>

            </task>


          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Try the same thing now with <m>u = \cos 3x</m>.
                What happens now?
              </p>
            </statement>

            </task>
        </exercise>
      </page>


      <page>
        <exercisegroup>
        <title>Combining Techniques</title>

        <introduction>
          <p>
            Try a substitution which transforms the integral into one suitable for parts.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int e^{\sqrt{3x+9}}\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>

          </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int\sin(\ln x)\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>

          </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use a trigonometric identity, then integrate by parts: <m>\int_0^{\pi/3} x\tan^2 x\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>

          </exercise>
        </exercisegroup>
      </page>


      <page>
        <exercisegroup>
        <title>Dirty tricks, part II</title>

        <introduction>
          <p>
            Use integration by parts with <m>dv = dx</m> to find the antiderivatives.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int\arctan x\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>

          </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int\operatorname{arcsec} x\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>

          </exercise>
        </exercisegroup>
      </page>


      <page>
        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Prove the reduction formula
              <me>
                \int \cos^nx\,dx = \frac{1}{n} \cos^{n-1}x \sin x + \frac{n-1}{n}\int\cos^{n-2}x\,dx.
              </me>
            </p>
          </statement>

          <hint>
            <p>
              You are going to integrate <em>something</em> by parts.
              How can you break up <m>\cos^n x\,dx</m> into <m>u \,dv</m> that makes <m>dv</m> easily to integrate?
            </p>
          </hint>
        </exercise>
      </page>
    </worksheet>
  </article>
</pretext>